{
  "texts": [
    "Chapter 3 Literature ReviewThe analysis of WCET is crucial for real-time system design to ensure tasks meet their deadlines.",
    "Accurate WCET understanding is essential for timing analysis and schedulability analysis during system certification, as real-time systems have stricter correctness criteria compared to general-purpose systems.",
    "Missing deadlines in these systems can lead to catastrophic consequences.WCET analysis techniques are divided into deterministic and probabilistic categories [38].",
    "Deterministic Timing Analysis (DTA) delivers a single WCET estimate based on the system's hardware and software resources producing an output within a defined time for a given input and initial state.",
    "Probabilistic Timing Analysis (PTA) computes a distribution function called probabilistic WCET (pWCET), accommodating resources with time-randomised or time-deterministic behavior.Both deterministic and probabilistic approaches have three variants each: static, measurement-based, and hybrid, resulting in six WCET analysis variants:• Static Deterministic Timing Analysis (SDTA)• Measurement-Based Deterministic Timing Analysis (MBDTA)• Hybrid Deterministic Timing Analysis (HYDTA)• Static Probabilistic Timing Analysis (SPTA)• Measurement-Based Probabilistic Timing Analysis (MBPTA)• Hybrid Probabilistic Timing Analysis (HYPTA)The following sections provide an overview of various research studies that employed different methods."
  ]
}